"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody, one of the things I'm looking to do is to uh expand my existing business, which really hasn't taken off yet, on farm compost LLC. And what I'm looking to do is create a business where I collect kitchen waste from restaurants, produce houses, uh, supermarkets, anybody who has a large quantity of kitchen waste where uh they can get rid of it, save their dumpster space, keeps their dumpster from being the bio waste that so many dumpsters that take organic waste become. Save their dumpsters for plastic and cardboard, give me all the organic waste, I'll come pick it up, just put it in the drums, I'll come pick it up, I'll take it to Meadville, Texas, where we will compost it. We are looking to sheet compost. That means we need thousands of these drums. We are looking to take large quantities of waste and make large quantities of soil. We have 14 acres that we want to reinvigorate, that we want to create enough soil so that we can do a large-scale farming project here, and we have to do that, or we want to do that through regenerative processes, of course, but also through sheet composting. We want to take large amounts of organic waste and large amounts of wood chips, compost them together here on the farm, where you inoculate the farm, the soil with the decay cycle, where you get the whole thing going from start to finish here on the farm. You don't make it somewhere else and then bring it here. You get the entire decay cycle occurring here, and that helps so much. A lot of the area that we have been composting on is much more alive than the rest of the area. It's very interesting to see that. And of course, we've been doing this for about two years, but that that bacteria has really worked into the areas that we've been composting on and it's become much more green in those areas, which is great to see. But that's the idea behind this is that we want to take the composting process, put it on the farm, and take that waste directly from its source. We don't need to put it in a landfill. We don't need to take it to a compost yard where it gets concentrated. We need to take that waste and spread it out. We need to dissipate it so that the land can digest it. All of the ways that we use or that we take care of waste concentrates it. That's the exact opposite of what we need to be doing. We need to be dispersing the waste because that's where it can go back into the lens, that's where it can be absorbed, that's where it can become fertility, that's where waste becomes gold. And the only way to do this is through collecting the waste and rediverting it. It's not hard. It's just that we have to restructure the way we collect our waste. Because honestly, the way we do it now is the is the intensive process. Taking the way sheet composting and spreading it out where we help our farmers and we help our waste products, our waste uh distributions, waste management. There's what we're looking for. When we're doing all this, that's what we can do, and that's what we should be doing. It solves so many problems. So that's what I'm trying to do. And you start by with baby steps. So I'm trying to get people in the Houston area who have restaurants or who have produce houses or have supermarkets who are manage supermarkets who have any access to a lot of waste that's going into a dumpster right now for a very small fee. I'll come pick that up and I'll save you the extra uh space that you would have put in your dumpster. But more than that, I'm gonna make your dumpster a much cleaner place because all that waste makes for stinky gross dumpsters. Put them in the sealed drums, I'll take care of it, no more stinky dumpsters, and you'll be helping the world. Thanks a lot, y'all.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hey everybody, one of the things I'm looking to do is to uh expand my existing business, which really hasn't taken off yet, on farm compost LLC.\",\n      \"start\": 0.16,\n      \"end\": 8.64,\n  